Training Manual:

Valuation Main Model and Operating Expenses Tabs

 

Two new tabs have been added on Trident for commercial valuations only.

These new tabs are

  • Valuation Main Model
  • Operating Expenses, these tabs are located as per the below:

 

 

NB: To ensure that you do not lose any information captured, it is very important for a User to always click on the ‘save’ icon after capturing information and before moving to another section.

  1. Valuation Main Model Tab

 

A commercial property valuation summary including motivation of, but not limited to Tenancy, Income and Expenditure, as well as other valuation parameters applied.

 

1.1Summarized Tenant Details

 

This section is purely for capturing a summary of Tenant Details. A user would need to group Tenant information together based on relevance. A detailed breakdown of all Tenant Details must still be captured on the Tenant Schedule Tab.

 

To capture the tenant details, you need to click on ‘Add Tenant’, the system will then display a row of fields that would need to be captured

 

 

 

For each row you capture, you can specify if this space or unit is Vacant Space or Lettable Area by clicking on the checkboxes.

An example of capturing space that isn’t lettable area would be if a User is capturing a cell tower, they would as an example capture 1 under ‘Amount of Units’, then specify the unit as m2 and not select this as lettable area by not clicking on the Lettable checkbox.

If Lettable Area has been ticked in the checkbox, this value will be added to the Total Lettable Area calculation. If it has not been selected, then it will not be included in the Total.

 

A user also has an option to specify if the space that they are capturing is either a m2 or a parking bay. These options are available under ‘Unit’. If a User is capturing parking bays, they should select ‘parking’ as the classification of space, then proceed to capture the number of parking bays under Amount of units then thereafter select ‘Parking Bay’ under Unit.

If anything, else other than parking is selected as the classification of space then a User will capture the size of the area under the Amount of Units then thereafter select m2 as the Unit type.

Once this information has been captured, you can proceed to capture multiple lines for the various tenants by clicking on ‘Add Tenant’. The bottom of this table will display the total amounts for the information that has been captured.

There is an option to ‘Delete’ should you need to do so, after clicking on delete the selected row will be removed from the list

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


 

Field Definitions for ‘Summarized Tenant Details’ section

 

Field Name

Date of Valuation

 

Year 1 Ends

 

Floor / Store / Unit Number

 

Tenant Classification

 

Definitions

The date of valuation as at Investec sign-off (i.e. The cashflow start date).

 

The "Year 1 Ends" date refers to the 12 months cashflow applicable to the valuation.

 

This is the cashflow that the subject property would be expected to generate if let at market related rentals, as at the date of valuation.

Unit, door, shop, storeroom no.  of property as identified or as reflected on the tenancy schedule, rent roll or building plans.

 

Refers to the quality of the tenant profile i.e.

 

Retail:

Anchors,

National - Undoubted,

National - Grey

National - Doubted

International - Undoubted,

International - Grey

International - Doubted etc.

National Franchise

Regional Franchise

SME (Local/Line Shops)

 

Office & Industrial:

Corporate, SME, National Government, Provincial Government, Local Municipalities etc.

 

Specialised:

Corporate, SME, National Government, Provincial Government, Local Municipalities etc.

 

 

 

 

 

Field Name

Classification of Space

 

Lettable Area (m²)

 

Gross Market Rental/m² /Month

 

Total Lettable Area (m²)

 

Definitions

Refers to the use of the premises, namely Offices, Industrial, Retail. Residential, Auxiliary Areas/Components (e.g. cell towers/mast).

 

This is the area that is rentalised in the valuation and is measured according to the definition as set out in the Sapoa Method of Measuring Floor Areas in Commercial and Industrial Buildings.

Essentially, this covers the entire floor, excluding major vertical penetrations of the floor such as stairs, lift shafts, flues, pipe shafts and vertical ducts which serve more than one floor of the building. It includes additional services such as stairs, dumbwaiters and lifts which exclusively serve a tenant occupying more than one floor.

Parking, yard space, cell towers and the likes are to be shown separately.

 

The gross monthly market rental / m² must include a basic rental plus an operating costs allowance (An operating cost allowance makes provision to recover items such as merchants association / marketing, initial pro-rata CID levies and other similar or incidental costs).

Note: The operating costs that relate to a typical gross market related lease, i.e. the pro-rata increase in rates and taxes as well as the tenants pro rata share of utilities must be completed in the operating cost model / tab.

Base (Net) Rental = R100 / m²
Op Cost Allowance = R30 / m² (Fixed Expenses)
Therefore Gross Market Rental = R130 / m²
Op Cost Recoveries = R25 / m² (Variable expenses)
Gross Income = R155 / m²
Gross Op Costs = R84 / m² (65% of Gross Rental)
Net income = R71 / m²

 

It is the total of the lettable areas under roof, as defined in "Lettable Area".

Parking, yard space, cell towers and the likes are to be shown separately.

 

 

 

 

 

Field Name

Total Gross Market Rental/Month

Weighted Average Rental

Definitions

This is the total of the subject properties Gross Market Rental Income per month.

Gross Market Rental is defined in the "Gross Market Rental / m² / month" tool tip.

 

The average weighted rental (total monthly rental divided by total lettable area) of all the tenants.

Field Definitions for ‘Property Details’ section

 

Field Name

Reason for Valuation

 

Property Type

 

Definitions

The reason for which the valuation has been instructed, namely Collateral Security, Revaluation, Take-over, Purchase of Property.

 

1. Collateral Security: Valuation of an unbonded property, to be bonded by IBL

 

2. Revaluation: Valuation of a property currently bonded to IBL

 

3. Take-over: Valuation of a property currently bonded by another institution, and to be bonded by IBL

 

5. Purchase: Valuation of a property to be funded and bonded by IBL

Indicates the type of property underlying the mortgage bond, namely Office, Industrial, Retail, Residential etc.

 

Field Name

Grading of Property

 

Type of Ownership

 

Definitions

The most commonly accepted building classifications are according to definitions as set out by MSCI, Sapoa and Rode for example in offices:-

Office

-P-grade (Prime grade): Top quality, modern space, generally, a pace-setter in establishing rentals and includes the latest or recent generation of building services, ample parking, a prestigious lobby finish and good views, or a good environment.

-A-grade: Not older than 15 years and buildings in this category have had major renovations. They feature high quality modern finishes, air conditioning, adequate on-site parking, with market rental near the top of the range.



- B-grade: Generally older buildings, but accommodation and finishes are close to modern standards as a result of refurbishments and renovation from time to time, airconditioned, on-site parking, unless special circumstances pertain.

- C-grade: Buildings with old style finishes, services and building systems. They may or may not be air-conditioned or have on-site parking.

Industrial

- Distribution Centre

- Hi-Tech

- Prime+: Refer to the definition for Prime, and features A-grade offices

- Prime: An industrial property (including warehouses and distribution centers) in which space is easily lettable because it satisfies each of the following prerequisites:
1. Generally, in a good condition;
2. Satisfactory macro access (i.e. access to freeway);
3. Satisfactory micro access (i.e. from street to building);
4. Proper loading facilities;
5. Eaves >6 m (excluding micro/ mini units);
6. Wide clear span of trusses (few internal pillars);
7. On ground level;
8. Adequate three-phase electrical power.
9. Roof insulation

- Prime-: Refer to the definition for Prime, and features C-grade offices

- Secondary: This is industrial space which is not classifiable as prime because it does not satisfy all nine prerequisites for prime space listed above.

Retail

- Super Regional Shopping Centre (> 100,000 m2 in total rentable area)

- Regional Shopping Centre (50,000 - 100,000 m2 total rentable area)

- Small Regional Shopping Centre (25,000 - 50,000 m2 total rentable area)

- Community Shopping Centre (12,000 - 25,000 m2 total rentable area)

- Neighborhood Shopping Centre (5,000 - 12,000 m2 total rentable area)

- Retail Warehouse

- Standalone Retail unit

Specialised

 

This refers to e.g. Freehold, Leasehold, Undivided Share, Sectional Title, Usufruct, Shareblock etc.

 

 

 

 

Field Name

Total Erf Extent/Sectional Area (m²)

 

Total Gross Lettable Area (m²)

 

Definitions

Is the total size of the property site/sectional area in square meters

 

Gross lettable area, also known as gross leasable area (GLA) is the amount of floor space, which is available for rent, excluding common area.

 

 

Field Name

Percentage of Market Rentals Used

 

Weighted Average Gross Rental Applied (/m²)

 

Definitions

Is the % of gross market rental / m2  applied to the valuation, and can be a premium (> 100%), market (= 100%) or a discount (< 100%) to the going rate in the area, for the grading of the subject property.

The percentage applied would be based on the subject properties defining characteristics, i.e. does it have additional features that a tenant would pay more or less than market for.

Example:

1. Two identical grade office buildings, one with 6 parking bays / 100m2 vs the other with only 4 parking bays / 100m2.

The building with more parking bays might command a higher office rental for the fact that parking might be at a premium.

2. Two identically sized industrial buildings, one with a 20:80, office: warehouse split (Standard Industrial) vs another with a 40:60 split (Non Standard).

The concept for the industrial building is that they would both have the same gross market rental / m2 based on the size of the buildings, and the one would be able to command a slightly higher / lower rental than the other based on the nonstandard make-up of the lettable area.

We are wanting to capture the base gross market rental / m2 for the area and then differentiate with the percentage used, so that we can compare buildings to each other and have an explanation for the difference.

 

The average weighted market rental (total monthly market rental divided by total lettable area) of all the tenants, factoring in the definition of gross lettable area.

 

 

 

Field Name

Market Growth Rate on Gross Rentals

 

Vacancy by Area

 

Definitions

Is the anticipated annual growth rate (not the contractual escalation rate agreed to in the leases) at which gross market rentals are expected to grow by annually, which may be different to the contractual escalation rate agreed to in the leases, market dependent.

 

Is the total gross lettable area which is not tenanted (occupied).

 

 

Field Name

Vacancy by Area (m²)

 

Vacancy by Area (%)

 

Vacancy by Income

 

Vacancy by Income (R )

 

Definitions

Is the total gross lettable area which is not tenanted (occupied) in square meters.

 

Is the total gross lettable area which is not tenanted (occupied) divided by the total gross lettable area of the building (i.e. the proportion of vacant GLA).

 

Is the total income applied to the vacant floor area of the property (GLA).

 

Is the total income applied to the vacant floor area in Rands.

 

 

 

 

 

Field Name

Vacancy by Income (%)

 

Long-term Vacancy Applied (%)

 

Definitions

Is calculated by taking the income applied to the vacant floor area divided by the total income of the total floor area of the property (including the vacant area).

 

Is the percentage of floor area which is assumed to be vacant in perpetuity (>35 years).

 

 

 

Field Name

Net Operating Expenses R / m² / month

 

Annual Expenses Escalation Rate (%)

 

Definitions

Is the gross operating expenses, less the recoverable expenses, resulting in net operating expenses (i.e. the total expenses which the landlord/owner of property is responsible for, that is not recoverable).

Is the rate at which expenses relating to the property are increased annually. This is linked to municipal escalations, maintenance contract escalation, and insurance escalations etc.

 

 

 

Field Name

Effective Monthly Expense Escalation Rate (%)

 

Standard Capitalisation Rate (%)

 

Definitions

Is the effective monthly interest rate at which expenses increase

Formula driven: =RATE(12,,-100,100+(F40*100))

 

It is the expected net operating income for year 1, assuming the entire building is let at open market rentals, divided by the purchase/transaction price, normally expressed as a percentage. This calculation ignores VAT, transfer duty and income tax, and assumes a cash transaction (in contrast to a paper-based sale).

 

 

 

 

 

Field Name

Long-term (10 Year) Escalation Rate (%)

 

Implied Discount Rate (%)

 

Definitions

The rate by which a rental increases in terms of a leaseback: A fully repairing and insuring lease (tenant pays all operating costs) for 10 years or longer (with typically 5-yearly rent reviews or fixed annual escalations) with a tenant with a strong covenant.

 

The implied discount rate is used to express an expected future cash stream in present-value terms. In most instances, the discount rate is equal to the hurdle rate.

Mathematically, the hurdle rate of a property is the sum of its market capitalization rate plus the expected constant growth rate of its cash flow in perpetuity (>50 years).

 

 

 

Field Name

Discount Rate Applied (%)

 

Effective Monthly Discount Rate Applied (%)

 

Definitions

It is the discount rate applicable to the cash flow of the subject property taking into account necessary adjustments such as the quality of the tenant profile and lease periods.

The nominal (annual) discount rate is divided by 12 to find the monthly discount rate for calculation of the present value of monthly payments.

=RATE(12,,-100,100+(F45*100))

 

 

Fields Definitions for ‘Regression Parameters’ section:

 

Field Name

Source: Industrial / Retail Regression

 

a

 

Definitions

Regression is a statistical method used to determine the strength and character of the relationship between the area let and the gross rate /m2 paid at the start of a lease.

It is used in this instance to suggest rental rates for given areas (m2).

y = a + bx

Where:
y = expected rental rate/m2
a = constant
b = slope
x = area

Represent the expected rental where the lettable area equals zero. Denoted as a constant in the regression equation.

 

 

 

Field Name

b

 

r

 

Regressionary Rental / m² / Month

 

Average Size / Lettable Area (m²)

 

Definitions

Represent the slope of the regression line, in the regression equation.

 

"r²" is the coefficient of determination. It measures the strength of the relationship between two variables. It can have any value between -1 and +1. A value of -1, indicates a strong negative relationship. A value of +1 indicates a strong positive relationship.

 

Calculated gross market rental based on the linear regression equation for a given gross lettable area.

 

The average of the total gross lettable areas of the premises concerned.

Field Definitions for ‘Final Calculations’ section:

 

Field Name

Gross Market Income: Year 1

 

Gross Market Income: Year 1 (/m²/month)

 

Net Normalised Expenses: Year 1

 

Definitions

The gross annual rental includes basic rental, operating costs, the initial pro-rata rates, and taxes as at the commencement date, merchants association/ marketing, initial pro-rate CID levy and other similar or incidental rental costs.

 

The gross monthly income divided by the gross lettable area (GLA) of the premises.

 

The gross property expenses, less reasonable recoverables equates to the net normalised expenses, annualised in the first year of cash flow.

 

 

Field Name

Net Normalised Expenses: Year 1 (/m²/month)

 

Vacancy Loss:

Year 1

 

Vacancy Loss: Year 1 (/m²/month)

 

Definitions

The gross property expenses, less reasonable recoverables equates to the net normalised expenses, annualised in the first year of cash flow divided by the GLA.

 

The loss of income based on the vacancy factor/ provision applied, that is deducted from the total gross annual income in the first year.

 

Is the rate/m2 of gross market income/m2 which is assumed to be vacant in perpetuity (>35 years).

 

 

Field Name

Net Normalised Market Income: Year 1

 

Net Normalised Market Income: Year 1 (/m²/month)

 

Standard Capital Value (R)

 

Definitions

It is determined by the gross income, less the vacancy provision, less the net market operating costs, resulting in the net normalised income in the first year.

 

The net normalised market income divided by the GLA of the premises.

 

Is the standard market value that is derived by dividing the net normalised annual income by the applicable market capitalisation rate.

 

 

 

Field Name

Standard Capital Value (/m²)

 

Plus Additional Bulk

 

Definitions

It is the standard market value divided by the GLA of the premises.

 

The practically useable unutilised bulk area available on the property, as per the Erf's approved zoning.

The valuer is expected to consider the following when considering whether or not to apply any unutilised bulk:
1. Is there a market on the subject property?
2. Is it practically feasible to develop the bulk on the site, considering parking/height/building lines etc.?
3. Are there numerous examples in the area where similar buildings/zoning have made use of this additional bulk?

 

 

Field Name

Plus Additional Bulk (R/bulk m²)

 

Plus / Minus PV of OCF (R)

 

OCF as a % of Standard Capital Value

 

Definitions

The market value rate/m² applied to the bulk area.

 

The "Top Slice" or "Under Slice" value as a result of the rental being either above or below market rentals.

 

The value of the OCF divided by the market value of the property expressed as a percentage.

 

 

Field Name

Less Short-term Vacancy (R)

 

Less Short-term Vacancy - Months

 

Definitions

The short-term vacancy is derived by the difference between the actual vacancy in terms of GLA, less the long-term vacancy provision applied, for an expected short-term period, which has been smoothed.

The anticipated number of months the valuer believes it will take to fully let the vacant space, considering the space may be let all at once or portions of this space over time.

 

 

 

Field Name

Less Short-term Vacancy - Smoothing Factor

 

Less Short-term Vacancy as a % of Standard Capital Value

 

Definitions

The probability of the vacant space being let in a specified period of time. A smoothing factor closer to zero assumes that the space will be let at the beginning of the anticipated period allowed for. While a smoothing factor of closer to one assumes that the space will be let towards the end of the anticipated period allowed for.

The value of the short-term vacancy provision divided by the net normalised market income for year 1 expressed as a percentage.

*** How does one relate value to net rental income? ***

 

Field Name

Less CAPEX Required

 

Less CAPEX Required /m²

 

Market Value

 

Market Value (/m²)

 

Definitions

The Capital Expenditure (CAPEX) amount is determined by taking the actual vacant GLA and applying a market cost to fit out the premises to a lettable state.

 

It is CAPEX amount divided by the gross lettable area of the vacant space.

 

This is the value that is derived after applying:

 

1. A gross market rental

2. A long-term vacancy

3. Net normalised market operating costs

4. A market-related capitalisation rate

 

To the applicable GLA and then making the necessary adjustments based on the following:

 

5. Signed leases (OCF/top-slice/under-slice)

6. Unutilised useable bulk

7. Short-term vacancy

8. CAPEX

The market value divided by the total gross lettable area.

as a % of GI

The clients net operating expenses (gross operating costs less recoveries) in Rand terms.

The net operating expenses as provided by MSCI (gross operating costs less recoveries) expressed as a percentage of the valuation's gross market annual income.

MSCI Net Op Expenses (R)

 

IBL Net Op Expenses
as a % of GI

 

IBL Net Op Expenses (R)

 

Definitions

The MSCI net operating expenses (gross operating costs less recoveries) in Rand terms.

The net normalised operating expenses used in the valuation (gross operating costs less recoveries) expressed as a percentage of the valuation's gross market annual income.

 

The IBL net normalised operating expenses (gross operating costs less recoveries) in Rand terms.

  1. Operating Expenses Tab

2.1Operating Expenses Table

 

This section is for the capturing of Client Gross Op Costs, MSCI Gross Op Costs, IBL Normalised Gross Op Costs along with comments. The rates captured on this table are per m2 per month.

 

The MSCI sections will be displayed for Investec internal users only.

 

The above table is a detailed breakdown list of various Operating Expenses.

The below Op Cost fields will be mandatory for users to capture the % of Total Op Costs

  • Insurance
  • Management Costs
  • R&M: Building Fabric
  • Audit Fees

 

 

The below rules are applied for the 4 above mentioned fields:

A User will need to first capture information on the Replacement Cost Schedule tab for the system to be able to calculate the IBL Normalised fields for both Insurance and R&M: Building Fabric. If a user only captures the % of Total Op Costs for both these fields without having populated the Replacement Cost Schedule tab, then the auto calculations for IBL for these fields will not be able to calculate.

For the system to calculate the IBL Normalised fields for Management Costs and Audit Fees, the Gross Market Income on the Valuation Main Model tab would need to have been calculated. If a user only captures the % of Total Op Costs for both these fields without the Gross Market Income been calculated, then the auto calculations for IBL for these fields will not be able to calculate.

NB: If there is no Total Lettable Area on the Valuation Main Model tab, the 4 fields will always display 0.

 

A User has an option to add Additional Expenses that may fall outside of the set list that has already been provided. A User is able to add these by clicking on the ‘Add Additional Expenses’ button

 

 

 

After clicking on this button, a new row will be displayed for the capturing of the additional expense

 

The fields highlighted in blue are auto calculated fields which will calculate based on the input data that has been captured.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


 

Fields Definitions for ‘Operating Expenses’ section

 

Field Name

Effective Date of Client Operating Expenses

 

Effective Date of MSCI Operating Expenses

 

Effective Date of IBL Normalised Operating Expenses

 

Definitions

The date at which the client operating expenses commence from.

 

The date at which the MSCI operating expenses commence from.

 

The date at which the IBL normalised operating expenses commence from.

 

NB: This date is important as it is the date that we use to grow the operating expenses by.

 

 

Field Name

Client Gross Annual Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

Client Recoveries (/m²)

 

Client Net Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

Definitions

Gross operating expenses generally cover all landlord property-related expenses. This amount is then divided by the gross lettable area of the premises.

 

Gross Operating costs do not take into account any recoveries.

Recoveries refer to expenses claimed back from tenants as per signed lease agreements. This amount is then divided by the gross lettable area of the premises.

Net Operating Expenses refers to the gross operating less any contractual recoveries.

 

 

 

Field Name

Number of Months to Escalate Expenses

 

MSCI Gross Annual Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

MSCI Gross Annual Recoveries (/m²)

 

Definitions

This is the number of months to escalate the IBL net normalised operating expenses by.

 

It is calculated by subtracting the Year 1 Ends date from the effective date of IBL normalised operating expenses.

 

This refers to the remaining period under review. These expenses are usually escalated at the normalised annual expense escalate rate.

Represents the gross operating costs /m2 as reported by MSCI for specific property types.

 

Gross operating expenses generally cover all landlord property-related expenses based on MSCI data. This amount is then divided by the gross lettable area of the premises.

 

Gross operating costs do not take into account any recoveries.

Represents the recoveries /m2 as reported by MSCI for specific property types.

 

Recoveries refer to expenses claimed back from tenants per the MSCI database. This amount is then divided by the gross lettable area of the premises.

 

 

 

 

Field Name

MSCI Net Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

IBL Normalised Gross Annual Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

IBL Normalised Gross Annual Operating Expenses (/m²)

 

Definitions

Represents the net operating costs /m2 as reported by MSCI for specific property types.

 

Net operating expenses refers to the gross operating less any contractual recoveries per the MSCI database.

This represents the gross operating costs /m2 for the subject property, based on specific property types, normalising in long-dated and non-recurring expenses (ie. bad debts, leasing commissions, and major CAPEX requirements such as replacing a building's central air-conditioning system, escalators, lifts etc).

 

Another example of normalising these operating costs would be where the actual municipal value is substantially lower than the anticipated market value. Hence, the municipal value is adjusted to market norms. This would translate into the assessment rates being increased/normalised accordingly. 

 

The IBL normalised expenses should factor in more than the bare minimum as we are taking a longer-term view, hence the itemised breakdown of operating costs provided.

 

Gross operating costs do not take into account any recoveries.

 

NB: Normalised expenses represent the process whereby a valuer adjusts the actual expenses by adding certain expenses that are unusual or long-dated, non-recurring items. The reason for adding them back in is to make provision for these long-dated items, thereby smoothing the effect on the market value rather than creating volatile movements in the property's value only in the year that they are expensed.

 

Please note that the effects of signed lease(s), where the lease rentals are considered above/below a typical gross market rental, must be factored into an OCF (top-slice/under-slice), provided that the underlying tenant(s) is considered financially sound.

Represents the normalised recoveries /m2 for specific property types.

 

Recoveries refer to expenses claimed back from tenants. This should represent a market-related scenario with the effect of the leases differing from market accounted for in the OCF (top-slice/under-slice).

 

Please note that the effects of signed lease(s), where the lease rentals are considered above/below a typical gross market rental, must be factored into an OCF (top-slice/under-slice), provided that the underlying tenant(s) is considered financially sound.

% of Total Op Expenses

 

Expenses Ending Year 1:

 

Definitions

Represents the IBL normalised gross Expenses less the Normalised Recoverables divided by the gross lettable area of the premises.

This represents the individual IBL net normalised expenses /m2 as a percentage of the total IBL net normalised expenses /m2.

The "Year 1 Ends" date refers to the 12 months cashflow applicable to the valuation.

 

This is the date that will be used to grow the expenses for the required period.

 

ie. If your expenses are correct as at 31 December 2019, and your year 1 ends date is 30 June 2020, then the model will grow your expenses by 6 months, using the expense escalation rate captured in the variables.

Definitions

This represents the IBL normalised net operating expenses, grown to the end of year 1.

 

ie. If your expenses are correct as at 31 December 2019, and your year 1 ends date is 30 June 2020, then the model will grow your expenses by 6 months, using the expense escalation rate captured in the variables.

This represents the IBL normalised net operating expenses, grown to the end of year 1, and divided by the the gross lettable area of the premises.

 

ie. If your expenses are correct as at 31 December 2019, and your year 1 ends date is 30 June 2020, then the model will grow your expenses by 6 months, using the expense escalation rate captured in the variables.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Operating Expenses List Definitions:

 

Field Name

Definition

Bad Debts

All Bad debt write offs and write downs within period

Includes: Bad Debts (accrued rental written off that year), legal expenses directly related to bad debts, debt collection expenses

Excludes: Current outstanding bad debts not written off as of submission

Building Management

All management fees associated with the building

Includes: Collection commission, external property managing agent fees (i.e. JHI). Where internally managed, it should include all cost related to direct management of the building not captured in Building Management Costs

Cleaning

All cleaning related expenditure

Includes: Contract and In-House; cleaning and bins, window cleaning, cleaning consumables, cleaner’s wages, carpet cleaning, hygienic services, pest control, sanitary consumables, specialist cleaning of individual units (where applicable)

Excludes: Municipal cleaning levies for surrounding areas, capitalised major cleanup operations, painting

Electricity

Electricity consumption, meter reading

Includes: Billed electricity consumption, meter reading, common area electricity consumption

Excludes: Capitalised electricity infrastructure upgrades, and rates and taxes

Gardens

All garden related expenditure

Includes: Garden exterior and interior, plants, landscaping, irrigation systems (contract, R&M), water features, salaries and wages for garden personnel, contracted garden services, contract costs

Insurance

All insurance related costs

Includes: Annual premium, broker fees, other Insurance related costs

Letting Fees and Commissions

All cost associated with the letting of the building

Includes: Letting commissions, lease renewal & new lease fees (i.e. only those paid to external brokers)

Management Costs

All management fees associated with the building

Includes: Collection commission, external property managing agent fees (i.e. JHI). Where internally managed, it should include all cost related to direct management of the building not captured in Building Management Costs

Municipal Charges

All other municipal costs not otherwise accounted for

Including but not exclusively: Water consumption, refuse, municipal land – rental, sewage, effluent, water meter reading

Rates and Taxes

All rates and taxes cost

Includes: Rates & taxes, BID/CID contributions

Excludes: Water consumption, refuse, municipal land – rental, sewage, effluent, water meter reading

R&M: Air Conditioning

All air-con related repairs and maintenance expenditure

Includes: Service contract air-con, repairs & maintenance, spare parts, air-con consumables and dedicated salaries of on-site staff, contracted air-con services, contract costs.

R&M: Building Fabric

All building repair and maintenance costs associated with that property excluding lifts, elevators, and air cons

Includes: Signage, electrical, plumbing, painting, repairs (external/internal), building materials, fixtures & fittings (common areas), name signs, ceilings, floors & carpets, general, structural repairs, mechanical equipment, waterproofing, waste compactor, contract fire equipment, fire equip. repairs, fuels & oils, tools, electrical consumables

R&M: Refurbishment/Elevators/Escalators

All lift and elevator related repairs and maintenance expenditure

Includes: Repairs and maintenance, parts, lift & escalator consumables, consulting fees, specialist fees

Excludes: Addition of new lifts and elevators where expenditure is capitalised.

Security

All security related expenditure

Includes: Contract security, access control, equipment & repairs, salaries and wages for security personnel, temporary guards, security equipment maintenance, uniforms, access cards

Other Operating Costs

All other operating costs not otherwise accounted for

Possibly including but not exclusively: License fees, canteen, stamp duty (on leases), levies paid (RSC), audit fees, professional fees (not covered in previous categories), legal expenses (excluding those relating to bad debts), general expenses and other amortization payments (non TI), net effects of ancillary businesses and non-capitalised refurbishment costs. Will also Include landlord marketing costs if present
